docs.abstract: Joe Biden swept Arizona, Florida and Illinois and Bernie Sanders continued to lose ground in the Democratic primary’s delegate count.
docs.snippet: Joe Biden swept Arizona, Florida and Illinois and Bernie Sanders continued to lose ground in the Democratic primary’s delegate count.
docs.lead_paragraph: Joseph R. Biden Jr. swept the three states that voted Tuesday: Florida, Illinois and Arizona. Bernie Sanders lost ground badly in the delegate count. And the coronavirus pandemic continued to wreak havoc on the most basic facets of American life, threatening to disrupt if not derail the remaining primary calendar.

headline.print_headline: 4 Takeaways From a Rout That Tightens Biden’s Grip

docs.abstract: Mr. Biden said he would pick a woman to be his vice presidential nominee. Here are several names in the mix, as well as factors on Mr. Biden’s mind.
docs.snippet: Mr. Biden said he would pick a woman to be his vice presidential nominee. Here are several names in the mix, as well as factors on Mr. Biden’s mind.
docs.lead_paragraph: Following Joseph R. Biden Jr.’s new pledge to choose a woman as his running mate if he becomes the Democratic presidential nominee, his campaign said on Monday that it would run a “vigorous vetting process” of possible vice-presidential candidates, fueling further curiosity among party members about whom he might pick.

headline.main: Behind Joe Biden’s Thinking on a Female Running Mate
headline.print_headline: A Guide to the Veepstakes: How Biden Is Sizing Up Potential Running Mates

docs.abstract: Joe Biden won all three states that held primary contests on Tuesday, forcing Bernie Sanders to reassess the future of his campaign in a race that has been upended by a public health crisis.
docs.snippet: Joe Biden won all three states that held primary contests on Tuesday, forcing Bernie Sanders to reassess the future of his campaign in a race that has been upended by a public health crisis.
docs.lead_paragraph: With the coronavirus pandemic front of mind, electoral politics may feel like a distant concern. Yet the Democratic primary is pressing on, even as the public health crisis has hugely altered it.

headline.main: Biden Takes Charge as Coronavirus Spreads: This Week in the 2020 Race

byline.original: By Maggie Astor and Matt Stevens

docs.abstract: Gov. Mike DeWine ignored a court ruling and said the state’s health director was closing the polls on Tuesday based on worries that the coronavirus placed voters and poll workers in potential danger.
docs.snippet: Gov. Mike DeWine ignored a court ruling and said the state’s health director was closing the polls on Tuesday based on worries that the coronavirus placed voters and poll workers in potential danger.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ohio’s governor on Monday night said he and top state health officials would ignore a court ruling and postpone Ohio’s presidential primary by declaring a public health emergency because of the coronavirus outbreak.

headline.main: Ohio’s Governor Postpones Primary as Health Emergency Is Declared Over Virus
headline.print_headline: Ohio Primary Off, Then On, And Then Off Once Again

byline.original: By Nick Corasaniti and Stephanie Saul

docs.abstract: Mr. Sanders and his aides are now struggling to reconcile a sense of resignation with a desire to press on, and some allies are urging the senator to stay in the race.
docs.snippet: Mr. Sanders and his aides are now struggling to reconcile a sense of resignation with a desire to press on, and some allies are urging the senator to stay in the race.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Bernie Sanders jabbed his finger in the air. He left Joseph R. Biden Jr. resorting to misstatements to defend his stance on bankruptcy legislation. He instructed viewers to “go to the YouTube” to check out the former vice president’s record themselves.

headline.main: Bernie Sanders Wants to Fight On. He Has His Reasons.
headline.print_headline: Despite a Bleak Outlook, Sanders Soldiers On

docs.abstract: Most bets are off as worries over the coronavirus hover over voting in Tuesday’s Democratic primaries, but Joe Biden has led in surveys of all three states.
docs.snippet: Most bets are off as worries over the coronavirus hover over voting in Tuesday’s Democratic primaries, but Joe Biden has led in surveys of all three states.
docs.lead_paragraph: Little is going as planned in Tuesday’s Democratic primaries. In parts of Florida and Arizona, some polling locations were unable to open in the morning after volunteers refused to show up because of worries about the coronavirus.

headline.main: What the Polls Say About Florida, Illinois and Arizona

docs.abstract: Arizona’s primary is on Tuesday, and Democrats there are holding onto the idea that they still have control over something: “I want to believe that voting takes away some of the fear.”
docs.snippet: Arizona’s primary is on Tuesday, and Democrats there are holding onto the idea that they still have control over something: “I want to believe that voting takes away some of the fear.”
docs.lead_paragraph: PHOENIX — Supermarket shelves are barren. Schools are closing across the country. But in Arizona, many Democrats are hoping that voting in the presidential primary provides a slice of normalcy at a time that is anything but normal.

headline.main: In Arizona, Voting During a Pandemic Is a Way to Feel Normal
headline.print_headline: Democrats Plan to Vote As Source of Comfort:  ‘What Is Normal Now?’

docs.abstract: The representative from Hawaii, who often defied her own party, announced the end of her campaign and said she would back Joe Biden.
docs.snippet: The representative from Hawaii, who often defied her own party, announced the end of her campaign and said she would back Joe Biden.
docs.lead_paragraph: Representative Tulsi Gabbard of Hawaii, who ran a foreign policy-focused campaign for the presidential nomination of a party she sharply criticized, announced on Thursday that she was dropping out of the race.

headline.main: Tulsi Gabbard Drops Out of Presidential Race
headline.print_headline: Hawaii’s Gabbard Quits Campaign for President And Will Support Biden

byline.original: By Lisa Lerer and Maggie Astor

docs.abstract: Discussions with 60 Democratic officials found that three former candidates — Kamala Harris, Elizabeth Warren and Amy Klobuchar — were their leading choices, followed by Stacey Abrams.
docs.snippet: Discussions with 60 Democratic officials found that three former candidates — Kamala Harris, Elizabeth Warren and Amy Klobuchar — were their leading choices, followed by Stacey Abrams.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. now holding an all but insurmountable lead over Senator Bernie Sanders in the presidential primary contest, many Democrats have shifted their attention to a favorite quadrennial parlor game: the vice-presidential search.

headline.main: Biden’s Running Mate? Party Leaders Favor Female Ex-Rivals
headline.print_headline: Biden Cut Field in Half, But It’s Still a Long List Of Vice President Picks

docs.abstract: It was the strongest sign yet that he plans to keep competing against Joe Biden in the Democratic presidential primary.
docs.snippet: It was the strongest sign yet that he plans to keep competing against Joe Biden in the Democratic presidential primary.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Bernie Sanders plans to participate in the Democratic presidential debate in April if one is held, his campaign said on Tuesday, the strongest indication yet that he plans to continue competing against Joseph R. Biden Jr. in the 2020 primary for the foreseeable future.

headline.main: Bernie Sanders Plans to Participate in Next Debate, Campaign Says

byline.original: By Sydney Ember and Reid J. Epstein
